\par 
\par }{\b The Lower Ward
\par 
\par }{\'93Sadly enough, the Lower Ward has been slipping in stature in the recent years and decades. Now with the fall of the factions, especially with the Godsmen for the most part departing the city, the ward is liable to fall into lower import as well. 

\par 
\par \'93For a ward once known as the Prime Ward, back during the days of the Incanterium and the Clueless Rebellion
, and once one of the largest wards in Sigil, the Lower Ward has certainly fallen far from what it once was. Now it seems it will be slowly absorbed in part by either the Hive or the Lady\rquote 
s Ward. The powers that be are seemingly eager to carve it apart like a roasted Quill at the dinner table, with all of them polishing their metaphorical knives in relish.
\par 
\par \'93But the future is never a certain thing, and the intrigues of Sigil are by far not a reliable topic for any diviner or sage, that is most definitely ce
rtain. What comes will come, and the workers, laborers, and shopkeepers of the ward will remain, regardless of the name and classification.\'94 \endash  The Editor
\par 
\par }{\b\i Great Foundry District
\par }{
\par About twelve blocks from the Great Foundry sits one of the ward\rquote s curiosities, a small magic shop known as the Friendly Fiend. Or rather, within the shop itself is the larger curiosity, the Friendly Fiend himself, A\rquote 
kin the Arcanoloth (N? male arcanoloth Sor6). A\rquote kin, both proprietor and owner, tends to be as large a draw at times as the contents of his shop itself.
\par 
\par The shop sells everything from barely magical baubles to animated objects of great value, as well as random items gathered from across the planes to be used as spell components or simply because they look neat upon a shelf collecting dust. A\rquote 
kin seems to be able to get his claws on nearly anything a cutter inquires about given some time, and he always does so with a smile.
\par 
\par That\rquote s what makes him an enigma; the fiend seems to be genuinely friendly with most anyone wandering through his shop. He\rquote ll greet a customer, recognize them by name and face if they ever walk in a second time, and he\rquote 
ll inevitably just give them some small trinket for stopping by if it strikes their fancy. His demeanor gets him customers just as much as his shop\rquote 
s contents, but it also gets him a great number of rumors and suspicious glares. After all, when was the last time ANYONE met a friendly fiend? It\rquote s all an act right? Well, maybe, and maybe not. None have ever in the centuries he\rquote 
s been in Sigil seen him act like a typical Yugoloth, even so much as see him act surly on a bad day. He\rquote 
s just always genuinely cheerful and talkative. It might just be a healthy way of spying on customers and their activities within the ward, or as some have suggested
 he may be an outcast of his own race for whatever reason, up to and even possibly including the fact that he may even be a risen fiend. A\rquote kin doesn\rquote 
t like to talk about his past, or the rumors about himself, and inevitably he just shrugs and soon enough the conversation is slid back to the health of the questioner and current happenings in their life. 
\par 
\par One thing is known however: for whatever reason, he\rquote s absolutely loathed by Sigil\rquote s other resident arcanoloth, Shemeska the Marauder. She\rquote s been known to fly into public fits if he\rquote 
s mentioned in the same breath as her. Fallen out compatriots? Former or current lovers? Siblings? Some combination of the above? Who knows, since neither is talking. She scowls and raves, and he just smiles as he dusts his shelve
s and asks about his customers. [A\rquote kin didn\rquote 
t have anything much to say about the rumors that as always regard him, but he did manage to sell a number of animated dolls to his interviewer, and gave them a few Arcadian mints before sending the confused truth seeker on their way with a smile. 
\endash  The Editor]
\par 
\par Moving on, just spireward of the Armory, but still a healthy number of blocks away, the neighborhoods grow seedi
er as the residents tend to be more worker than artisan, and more fiend than otherwise. Here, along Ironmonger Street, is the tavern and often riot in the making, the Styx Oarsman. Primarily a Tanar\rquote 
ri bar, it also serves Yugoloths, but refuses to so much 
as let Baatezu through the heavily barred and guarded doors. The inn is the haunt of many a fiendish criminal, crosstrader, fence, and among the most famous of them is Rule-Of-Three. The wizened, one-eyed githzerai often finds his name associated, but nev
er proven, with many a number of crimes and Tanar\rquote ri plots in the ward and across the Cage. [Githzerai? He\rquote s more a fiend than half the patrons of the Oarsman. And he\rquote 
s not of the friendly variety, take my word. Though he gets things done if you don\rquote t mind listening to, or otherwise talking to him in patterns of three. \endash  The Editor]
\par 
\par }{\b The Great Foundry}{ - The source of the ever present dusting of ash, soot, and smog that blankets the majority of the Lower Ward in its ever present yellow haze, the Great Foundry
 continues to belch forth the wastes of the forges and furnaces within. It and the district that surrounds it sits at the very center of the Lower Ward, with everything else clustered around and usually in some way relating to the production, sale, and di
stribution of its smokestack birthed fruits.
